  "id": "MAL-2026-5418",
  "summary": "Malicious code in @nstrlabs/api-client (npm)",
  "details": "\n---\n_-= Per source details. Do not edit below this line.=-_\n\n## Source: amazon-inspector (21dda1fd78fda4debfc14241cb2f5653bb328ccbe744170341d7f5a93331dac2)\npackage.json sets `preinstall: node index.js`, which runs automatically on `npm install`. index.js collects host metadata (os.hostname(), os.userInfo().username, __dirname, process.cwd()), hex-encodes the JSON as DNS labels, and resolves them under `*.d8jbmnsqcfu78dfs8vdg34ohqhirb4pbg.oast.live` (an interactsh-style OOB DNS exfiltration channel). It additionally POSTs the same JSON payload to the bare IP `http://172.201.213.59:9090/c`. Both channels fire unconditionally at install time. The package coordinates (`@nstrlabs/api-client` at version `99.0.1`, description `security research`, no real functionality beyond the beacon) match the canonical dependency-confusion pattern: a high version number is published to the public registry to override resolution of an internal `@nstrlabs` scope, leaking installer host data from any CI/build that resolves the scope publicly.\n",
